{{redirect|Angolar|the Angolan currency|Angolan angolar}} {{Infobox language |name = Angolar Creole |nativename = ''n'golá'' |states = [[São Tomé and Príncipe]] |speakers = 5,000 |date=1998 |ref=e18 |familycolor = Creole |fam1 = [[Portuguese-based creole|Portuguese Creole]] |fam2 = Lower Guinea |iso3=aoa |glotto=ango1258 |glottorefname=Angolar |lingua=51-AAC-ad }}
'''Angolar Creole''' is a minority [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]-based [[creole language]] of [[São Tomé and Príncipe]], spoken in the southernmost towns of [[São Tomé Island]] and sparsely along the coast, especially by [[Angolares|Angolar]] people. It is also called by its native speakers as ''n'golá''. It is a [[creole language]], based on [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] with a heavy substrate of a dialect of [[Kimbundu language|Kimbundu]] (port. Quimbundo), a [[Bantu language]] from inland [[Angola]], where many had been enslaved.
According to their external history, the following three types of creole have been distinguished: #plantation creoles, #fort creoles, #maroon creoles (Bickerton 1988)
Angolar Creole is considered a maroon creole.<ref>http://semantics.uchicago.edu/kennedy/classes/sum07/myths/creoles.pdf</ref>
