'''Cináed ua hArtacáin''' (died 975) was an [[Irish people|Irish]] [[Irish language|Gaelic]] [[poet]].

The chief poet of [[Leth Cuinn]] according to the [[Annals of Tigernach]] and the chief poet of all Ireland according to the [[Annals of Ulster]], Cináed wrote [[dinsenchas]] pertaining to the [[Kings of Brega|Kingdom of Brega]].<ref name="oxforddnb.com">John Carey, "Cináed ua hArtacáin [Cineth O'Hartagain] (d. 975)", ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', Oxford University Press, 2004, [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/20636 accessed 22 Nov 2016]</ref> [[Edward O'Reilly (scholar)|Edward O'Reilly]] gives a full account of his works in his 'Irish Writers', LXXXVIII sq.; d. anno 975.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YZIFAAAAQAAJ&pg=PP9&dq=%22edward+O'Reilly%22+irish+writers&hl=en&ei=94UGTKPzBZaa_Qa3yIWODA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCwQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Transactions of the Iberno-Celtic Society for 1820 |publisher=Iberno-Celtic Society |year=1820|location=Dublin |volume=Vol I |issue=Part I |accessdate=2010-06-11}}</ref> A marginal note in the [[Annals of Ulster]] suggests he was one of the southern branch of the [[Uí Néill]] dynasty of [[Síl nÁedo Sláine]].<ref name="oxforddnb.com"/> Apart from the year of his death (975), no further facts are known about his life.

His most ambitious poem was a list of the graves of prominent warriors entitled ‘Fianna bátar i nEmain’.<ref name="oxforddnb.com"/> He wrote a eulogy for the Brega king [[Congalach mac Mael Mithig]] (died 956).<ref>[http://www.ricorso.net/rx/az-data/authors/c/Cinaed/life.htm "Cináed Ó hArtacáin"], Ricorso: A Knowledge of Irish Literature, 1990-2010, devised and compiled by Bruce Stewart, accessed 22 November 2016</ref> He also appears to have been patronised by the [[Viking]] king of Dublin [[Olaf Cuaran|Olaf Cuarán]] (Olaf Sihtricson).<ref name="oxforddnb.com"/>

