'''Cuyo Spanish''' or '''Cuyano Spanish''' (Español Cuyano) is the [[dialect]] of [[Spanish language|Spanish]] that evolved in the [[Cuyo Province|historical province of Cuyo]] and that is now spoken in the Argentine provinces of [[Mendoza Province|Mendoza]] and [[San Juan Province, Argentina|San Juan]]. To a lesser extent it is also spoken in the provinces of [[San Luis Province|San Luis]] and [[La Rioja Province, Argentina|La Rioja]]. Cuyo Spanish shares a series of common traits with [[Chilean Spanish]] due to settlement history and commercial ties. Later on, under the Argentine Republic [[Rioplatense Spanish]], the dialect of [[Buenos Aires]] and [[Uruguay]] influenced Cuyo Spanish.   

