| colspan="2" | {{IPA|ʌɪ̯~ɜɪ̯~ɐɪ̯}}<ref name="canadianraising">Some dialects of North American English have a vowel shift called [[Canadian raising]], in which the first element of the diphthongs {{IPA|/aɪ, aʊ/}} is raised in certain cases, yielding {{IPA|[ʌɪ̯, ʌʊ̯]}} or {{IPA|[əɪ̯, əʊ̯]}}. Canadian English has raising of both diphthongs, but most dialects in the United States only have raising of {{IPA|/aɪ/}}. In monosyllables, raising occurs before voiceless consonants, so ''right'' {{IPA|[ɹʌɪ̯t]}} and ''out'' {{IPA|[ʌʊ̯t]}} have raised vowels, but ''eyes'' {{IPA|[aɪz]}} and ''loud'' {{IPA|[laʊd]}} do not.</ref>
