{{for|the sports shooter|Kunzang Choden (sport shooter)}} {{Infobox writer | name = Kunzang Choden | image = Kunzang Choden.jpg | imagesize = 150px | caption = Choden after a book reading in</br> [[Washington, DC]]. | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth year and age|1952}} | birth_place = [[Bumthang District]], [[Bhutan]] | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = | nationality = [[Bhutan]]ese | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = [[University of Nebraska-Lincoln]] | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | notableworks = The Circle of Karma | spouse = | partner = | children = 2 daughters, 1 son | relatives = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | signature = | website = {{URL|1=http://www.zubaanbooks.com/zubaan_author_details.asp?AuthorID=16}} | portaldisp = }}
'''Kunzang Choden''' (born 1952)<ref>Zubaan Books. [http://www.zubaanbooks.com/circleofkarma/ Circle of Karma website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020045539/http://www.zubaanbooks.com/circleofkarma/ |date=2007-10-20 }}.</ref> is a [[Bhutan]]ese writer. She is the first Bhutanese woman to write a novel in English.
Choden was born in [[Bumthang District]]. Her parents were feudal landlords. At the age of nine, her father sent her to school in India, where she learned English.<ref>Avijit Ghosh. "[http://www.telegraphindia.com/1050403/asp/look/story_4562286.asp Coming full circle]." ''[[The Telegraph (Kolkata)]]''. 3 April 2005.</ref> She has a BA Honours in [[Psychology]] from [[Indraprastha College]] in [[Delhi]] and a BA in [[Sociology]] from the [[University of Nebraska-Lincoln]]. She has worked for the [[United Nations Development Program]] in Bhutan. She and her Swiss husband currently live in [[Thimphu]].<ref>[http://www.zubaanbooks.com/zubaan_author_details.asp?AuthorID=16 Zubaan Books] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020052006/http://www.zubaanbooks.com/zubaan_author_details.asp?AuthorID=16 |date=2007-10-20 }}</ref>
''The Circle of Karma'', published 2005, is her first novel. It takes place in the 1950s, the initial period of imperially regulated [[modernization]] in Bhutan. The main character, a [[Women in Bhutan|Bhutanese woman]] and road-builder by occupation, is forced to deal both with the traditional, restrictive [[gender role]]s of pre-modern Bhutan and the new kinds of [[sexism]] developing as men gain economic freedom.<ref>Anna Sujatha Mathai. "[http://www.hindu.com/mag/2005/07/17/stories/2005071700370500.htm Rooted in the soil and earth]". ''[[The Hindu]]''. 17 July 2005.</ref>
==Bibliography== * ''Folktales of Bhutan'' (1994) {{ISBN|974-8495-96-5}} * ''Bhutanese Tales of the Yeti'' (1997) {{ISBN|1-879155-83-4}} * ''Dawa: The Story of a Stray Dog in Bhutan'' (2004) {{ISBN|99936-644-0-5}} * ''The Circle of Karma'' (2005) {{ISBN|81-86706-79-8}} * '' Chilli and Cheese- Food and Society in Bhutan'' (2008) {{ISBN|978-974-480-118-0}} * '' Tales in Colour and other stories'' (2009) {{ISBN|978-81-89884-62-8}}
